Fitz-Hamon, though certainly a severe conqueror, probably, like the greater conqueror under whom he had served‚ did not disturb the Welsh more than was necessary for his own security, though that, no doubt, is admitting a good deal. Einion and other Welsh lords were permitted to retain large tracts on the hills; and of four of tho sons of J estyn, the eldest was allowed to hold a member-lordship in the low country on at least equa] terms with the greatest of the Nor- mans. The position held by the descendants of Oara- doc ap J estyn is unlike any retained in England by men of pure Saxon descent. They built a oastle on the Avan‚ established under its protection a chartered borough town, were lar e benefactors to Neath and Margam‚ two Norman Ahbeya burying at the latter, and, as their seals shoW, used annonial bearings and armour like the Normans. With all this they con- tinued for four generations to bear Welsh names, and to sympathise with the Welsh people; for which they were sometimes summoned to do personal homage to the king, and sometimes called upon to give hostages for their conduct. lt was Morgan ap Caradoc who, in 1188, convoyed Archbishop Baldwin across the treach- erous sande of Avan and Neath, on his way to Swansea.
